<exercise xml:id="reading-question-opposite-of-an-order" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Opposite of an order
  </title>
  
  <idx>
    opposite
  </idx>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Recall from <xref ref="problem-opposites-and-symmetry"/> that the <term> opposite </term> <m> \op{ R } </m> of a binary relation <m> R </m> on a set <m> X </m> is the binary relation defined by
      
      <md>
        \op{ R } = \setmid{ \of{ x_{ 2 } , x_{ 1 } } \in X^{ 2 } }{ \of{ x_{ 1 } , x_{ 2 } } \in R }
      </md>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that the opposite of a preorder is a preorder.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        asdf
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that the opposite of a partial order is a partial order.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        asdf
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that the opposite of a total order is a total order.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        asdf
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>
